  "text": "Heterogeneous choice versus generalized ordered logit models [CITATION_1] notes that the proportional odds assumption 9 of the ordered logit model is often violated. He shows that using generalized ordered logit models are one way of dealing with the problem. We will now illustrate that heterogeneous choice models may also be attractive alternatives. [CITATION_2] present data from the 1977 and 1989 general social survey in which respondents were asked to evaluate the following statement: \"A working mother can establish just as warm and secure a relationship with her child as a mother who does not work.\" Responses were coded as 1 = strongly disagree (1SD), 2 = disagree (2D), 3 = agree (3A), and 4 = strongly agree (4SA). Explanatory variables are yr89 (survey year; 0 = 1977, 1 = 1989), male (0 = female, 1 = male), white (0 = nonwhite, 1 = white), age (measured in years), ed (years of education), and prst (occupational prestige scale). ologit yields the following results:",
